{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480765","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480765"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:51:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:51:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"107"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"107","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/107"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.05,0.72,0.04,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"107"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103530"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"107","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/107"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"107"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85946"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"98"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"1196"},{"type":"tags","id":"2196"},{"type":"tags","id":"2956"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"14434"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16105"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17445"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17453"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17483"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32585"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39703"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41990"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42967"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103530","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103530"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 64-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for a routine check-up. He feels generally well. He has a medical history of type 2 diabetes, hyperlipidaemia, gout and right knee osteoarthritis. He is an active smoker with a 20 pack-year smoking history. His current medications are metformin, atorvastatin, allopurinol and ibuprofen as needed for knee pain. He does not take any regular medications for blood pressure control.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with a BMI of 31 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. His pulse rate is 72/min, blood pressure 155/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Review of his records shows persistent hypertension with blood pressure between 150-160 mmHg systolic and 85-95 mmHg diastolic over successive visits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EeGFR: 75 mL/min/1.73m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E (\u0026gt;90)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EElectrolytes: within normal limits\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHbA1c: 7.6% (4.0-6.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrine albumin:creatinine ratio: 16.4 mg/mmol (\u0026lt;2.5) [Previous urine albumin:creatinine ratio 2 months ago: 13.2 mg/mmol].\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate for management of his hypertension?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Atenolol","Hydrochlorothiazide","Perindopril","Spironolactone","Amlodipine"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with multiple modifiable cardiovascular risk factors, including untreated hypertension, suboptimal glycaemic control, obesity, and active smoking. He also shows evidence of diabetic nephropathy, given his urine results indicate \u0027moderately increased albuminuria\u0027 (formerly termed \u0027microalbuminuria\u0027), referring to a urinary albumin:creatinine ratio of 2.5-25 mg/mmol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPerindopril\u003C/strong\u003E, an ACE inhibitor, is the most appropriate choice for managing this patient\u0027s hypertension and stage 2 CKD (eGFR 75 mL/min/1.73m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E with microalbuminuria). ACE inhibitors and angiotensin receptor blockers (ARBs) are preferred first-line agents in patients with diabetic nephropathy and chronic kidney disease due to their renoprotective effects. They also provide cardiovascular protection, which is crucial given this patient\u0027s multiple risk factors. An ACE inhibitor should be initiated and uptitrated to the maximum tolerated dose to reduce albuminuria and renal function decline. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is worth noting that this patient is taking ibuprofen (an NSAID) as needed for knee pain. While the combination of an ACE inhibitor and NSAID can potentially increase the risk of acute kidney injury, this combination is acceptable as long as there is no concurrent diuretic use (the \u0022triple whammy\u0022 effect), the patient maintains adequate hydration, and renal function is monitored regularly. The patient\u0027s current eGFR of 75 mL/min/1.73m\u00b2 allows for cautious co-prescription with appropriate monitoring.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmlodipine\u003C/strong\u003E, a calcium channel blocker, has some anti-albuminuric effect, though less than ACE inhibitors/ARBs. While it could be considered as an alternative or add-on therapy, it is not the first choice in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHydrochlorothiazide\u003C/strong\u003E should be avoided in this patient due to his history of gout, as thiazide diuretics can exacerbate gout by increasing uric acid levels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAtenolol\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended as a first-line antihypertensive agent due to its less effective blood pressure-lowering effect compared to other classes. Additionally, beta-blockers may mask symptoms of hypoglycaemia in diabetic patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESpironolactone\u003C/strong\u003E is typically reserved for use as an additional agent when monotherapy is insufficient to control blood pressure. It is not a first-line choice for this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn addition to starting perindopril, management should include aggressive addressing of other modifiable risk factors, including smoking cessation, weight loss, and optimizing glycaemic control. Regular monitoring of renal function and electrolytes is important when initiating ACE inhibitor therapy, even in patients without CKD.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["ACE inhibitors or angiotensin receptor blockers are first-line treatments for hypertension in patients with diabetic nephropathy due to their renoprotective effects.","Moderately increased albuminuria (formerly microalbuminuria) is defined as a urinary albumin:creatinine ratio of 2.5-25 mg/mmol or urine albumin level of 30-300 mg/24hr.","Multiple modifiable cardiovascular risk factors should be addressed aggressively in patients with type 2 diabetes and hypertension."],"references":["Guideline for the diagnosis and management of hypertension in adults (2016). National Heart Foundation of Australia. Available at: https://www.heartfoundation.org.au/images/uploads/publications/PRO-167_Hypertension-guideline-2016_WEB.pdf","Cryer MJ, Horani T, DiPette DJ. Diabetes and Hypertension: A Comparative Review of Current Guidelines. J Clin Hypertens (Greenwich). 2016 Feb;18(2):95-100. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26234374/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85946"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"107"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85946","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85946"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-23T14:03:53+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-25T21:32:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"107"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103530"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://a